#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:5
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:7
msgid ""
"This RFC improves interoperation between APIs with different error types. It "
"proposes to:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:10
msgid ""
"Increase the flexibility of the `try!` macro for clients of multiple "
"libraries with disparate error types."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:13
msgid ""
"Standardize on basic functionality that any error type should have by "
"introducing an `Error` trait."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:16
msgid "Support easy error chaining when crossing abstraction boundaries."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:18
msgid ""
"The proposed changes are all library changes; no language changes are needed "
"-- except that this proposal depends on [multidispatch](https://github.com/"
"rust-lang/rfcs/pull/195) happening."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:22
msgid "Motivation"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:24
msgid ""
"Typically, a module (or crate) will define a custom error type encompassing "
"the possible error outcomes for the operations it provides, along with a "
"custom `Result` instance baking in this type. For example, we have `io::"
"IoError` and `io::IoResult<T> = Result<T, io::IoError>`, and similarly for "
"other libraries. Together with the `try!` macro, the story for interacting "
"with errors for a single library is reasonably good."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:31
msgid ""
"However, we lack infrastructure when consuming or building on errors from "
"multiple APIs, or abstracting over errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:34
msgid "Consuming multiple error types"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:36
msgid ""
"Our current infrastructure for error handling does not cope well with mixed "
"notions of error."
msgstr ""

