msgid ""
"Ideally, one could use the `try!` macro as in the `download` example to "
"coalesce a variety of error types into this single, simple `struct`."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:97
msgid "Library error reporting: abstraction boundaries"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:99
msgid ""
"When one library builds on others, it needs to translate from their error "
"types to its own. For example, a web server framework may build on a library "
"for accessing a SQL database, and needs some way to \"lift\" SQL errors to "
"its own notion of error."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:104
msgid ""
"In general, a library may not want to reveal the upstream libraries it "
"relies on -- these are implementation details which may change over time. "
"Thus, it is critical that the error type of upstream libraries not leak, and "
"\"lifting\" an error from one library to another is a way of imposing an "
"abstraction boundaries."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:110
msgid ""
"In some cases, the right way to lift a given error will depend on the "
"operation and context. In other cases, though, there will be a general way "
"to embed one kind of error in another (usually via a [\"cause chain\"]"
"(http://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/essential/exceptions/chained.html)). "
"Both scenarios should be supported by Rust's error handling infrastructure."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:116
msgid "Abstracting over errors"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:118
msgid ""
"Finally, libraries sometimes need to work with errors in a generic way. For "
"example, the `serialize::Encoder` type takes is generic over an arbitrary "
"error type `E`. At the moment, such types are completely arbitrary: there is "
"no `Error` trait giving common functionality expected of all errors. "
"Consequently, error-generic code cannot meaningfully interact with errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:125
msgid ""
"(See [this issue](https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/15036) for a "
"concrete case where a bound would be useful; note, however, that the design "
"below does not cover this use-case, as explained in Alternatives.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:130
msgid ""
"Languages that provide exceptions often have standard exception classes or "
"interfaces that guarantee some basic functionality, including short and "
"detailed descriptions and \"causes\". We should begin developing similar "
"functionality in `libstd` to ensure that we have an agreed-upon baseline "
"error API."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:136
msgid "Detailed design"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:138
msgid ""
"We can address all of the problems laid out in the Motivation section by "
"adding some simple library code to `libstd`, so this RFC will actually give "
"a full implementation."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:142
msgid ""
"**Note**, however, that this implementation relies on the [multidispatch]"
"(https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/pull/195) proposal currently under "
"consideration."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:146
msgid ""
"The proposal consists of two pieces: a standardized `Error` trait and "
"extensions to the `try!` macro."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:149
msgid "The `Error` trait"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:151
msgid ""
"The standard `Error` trait follows very the widespread pattern found in "
"`Exception` base classes in many languages:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:163
msgid ""
"Every concrete error type should provide at least a description. By making "
"this a slice-returning method, it is possible to define lightweight `enum` "
"error types and then implement this method as returning static string slices "
"depending on the variant."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:168
msgid ""
"The `cause` method allows for cause-chaining when an error crosses "
"abstraction boundaries. The cause is recorded as a trait object implementing "
"`Error`, which makes it possible to read off a kind of abstract backtrace "
"(often more immediately helpful than a full backtrace)."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:174
msgid ""
"The `Any` bound is needed to allow _downcasting_ of errors. This RFC "
"stipulates that it must be possible to downcast errors in the style of the "
"`Any` trait, but leaves unspecified the exact implementation strategy.  (If "
"trait object upcasting was available, one could simply upcast to `Any`; "
"otherwise, we will likely need to duplicate the `downcast` APIs as blanket "
"`impl`s on `Error` objects.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:181
msgid ""
"It's worth comparing the `Error` trait to the most widespread error type in "
"`libstd`, `IoError`:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:192
msgid ""
"Code that returns or asks for an `IoError` explicitly will be able to access "
"the `kind` field and thus react differently to different kinds of errors. "
"But code that works with a generic `Error` (e.g., application code) sees "
"only the human-consumable parts of the error. In particular, application "
"code will often employ `Box<Error>` as the error type when reporting errors "
"to the user. The `try!` macro support, explained below, makes doing so "
"ergonomic."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:200
msgid "An extended `try!` macro"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:202
msgid ""
"The other piece to the proposal is a way for `try!` to automatically convert "
"between different types of errors."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:205
msgid ""
"The idea is to introduce a trait `FromError<E>` that says how to convert "
"from some lower-level error type `E` to `Self`. The `try!` macro then passes "
"the error it is given through this conversion before returning:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:211
msgid ""
"// E here is an \"input\" for dispatch, so conversions from multiple error\n"
"// types can be provided\n"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:240
msgid ""
"This code depends on [multidispatch](https://github.com/rust-lang/rfcs/"
"pull/195), because the conversion depends on both the source and target "
"error types.  (In today's Rust, the two implementations of `FromError` given "
"above would be considered overlapping.)"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:246
msgid ""
"Given the blanket `impl` of `FromError<E>` for `E`, all existing uses of "
"`try!` would continue to work as-is."
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:249
msgid ""
"With this infrastructure in place, application code can generally use "
"`Box<Error>` as its error type, and `try!` will take care of the rest:"
msgstr ""

#: src/0201-error-chaining.md:261
msgid ""
"Library code that defines its own error type can define custom `FromError` "
"implementations for lifting lower-level errors (where the lifting should "
"also perform cause chaining) -- at least when the lifting is uniform across "
"the library. The effect is that the mapping from one error type into another "
"only has to be written one, rather than at every use of `try!`:"
msgstr ""

